I have implemented the Flutter-to-React Bridge "like a pro" by creating a dedicated singleton utility that handles native events, promise-based communication, and automatic environment detection.

1. The Bridge Engine (

flutterBridge.js
)
I created a robust bridge at 

src/utils/flutterBridge.js
. It features:

Auto-Detection: Automatically detects if the app is running inside Flutter.
Haptic Feedback: Support for triggered native vibrations.
Camera Integration: A clean 

openCamera()
 method that returns a standard JavaScript 

File
 object, making it compatible with all existing upload logic without further refactoring.
2. Implementation in UI
Work Completion Modal: I hijacked the camera button. In Flutter, it now triggers the high-resolution native camera directly.
Image Uploader: Added a premium "Capture from Camera" button that appears only when the app is running in the Flutter environment.
[Flutter Side Code] - bridge_handlers.dart
Copy and paste this code into your Flutter project where your InAppWebView is initialized.

A. JavaScript Handlers
dart
// inside onWebViewCreated or as a separate helper
void setupJavaScriptHandlers(InAppWebViewController controller) {
  
  // 1. Camera Handler
  controller.addJavaScriptHandler(handlerName: 'openCamera', callback: (args) async {
    final ImagePicker picker = ImagePicker();
    // Capture photo
    final XFile? photo = await picker.pickImage(
      source: ImageSource.camera,
      imageQuality: 80,
    );
    if (photo != null) {
      final bytes = await photo.readAsBytes();
      final String base64Image = base64Encode(bytes);
      
      return {
        'success': true,
        'base64': 'data:image/jpeg;base64,$base64Image',
        'fileName': photo.name,
        'mimeType': 'image/jpeg'
      };
    }
    return {'success': false, 'error': 'USER_CANCELLED'};
  });
  // 2. Haptic Feedback Handler
  controller.addJavaScriptHandler(handlerName: 'haptic', callback: (args) {
    // Requires services.dart
    HapticFeedback.mediumImpact();
    return {'success': true};
  });
}
B. WebView Lifecycle (Critical)
Ensure you dispatch the "Ready" event so React knows the bridge is active:

dart
InAppWebView(
  onLoadStop: (controller, url) async {
    // Tell React the bridge is ready
    await controller.evaluateJavascript(source: """
      window.dispatchEvent(new Event('flutterInAppWebViewPlatformReady'));
    """);
  },
  onWebViewCreated: (controller) {
    setupJavaScriptHandlers(controller);
  },
)
This bridge allows you to add any future native features (GPS, Contacts, Storage) simply by adding a new addJavaScriptHandler in Dart and calling flutterBridge.callHandler('name') in React.